'The sea is ours': landlocked Bolivia hopes court will reopen to Pacific
Sailors patrol a canvas-covered naval quarters in La Paz.
Public buildings fly a navy blue flag.
Fleet bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon are plastered with the slogan: "The sea is ours by right.
It is a duty to get it back".
Throughout landlocked Bolivia, the memory of the coastline lost to Chile in a bloody 19th-century resource conflict is fresh - as is the need to navigate the Pacific again.
That hope is probably the highest it has been in decades, as Bolivia awaits a ruling by the international court of justice on October 1, after 5 years of deliberations.
"Bolivia has the momentum, the spirit of unity and peace, and of course it expects the outcome with a positive attitude", said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will be watching the IGH ruling on large screens across the country, hoping that the tribunal in The Hague will find in favor of Bolivia's claim that  after decades of sporadic negotiations  Chile is obliged to negotiate to give Bolivia a sovereign passage to the sea.
Evo Morales, Bolivia's charismatic indigenous president  who faces a controversial reelection battle next year  also has much riding on Monday's ruling.
"We are close to returning to the Pacific", he promised in late August.
But some analysts believe that the court in Bolivia is unlikely to rule in favor of Bolivia  and that little will change if it does.
The Netherlands-based UN body has no power to allocate Chilean territory, and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of possible negotiations.
The fact that the IRH ruling comes only six months after the last hearing shows that the case "was not complicated", says Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
And rather than help Bolivia's cause, the past four years may have slowed it down.
"The issue of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian administration", Zárate said.
Morales' aggressive rhetoric had drained any remaining Chilean goodwill, she suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will resume talks at some point, but it will be very difficult to hold such talks.
The two countries last exchanged ambassadors in 1962.
Former president Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia's representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court's decision was extraordinarily quick.
Monday will bring Bolivia "an extraordinary opportunity to begin a new era of relations with Chile" and a chance to "end 139 years of differences with mutual benefits", he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales - still one of Latin America's most popular presidents - is using the maritime issue as a political crutch.
Bolivia will never give up its right of access to the Pacific Ocean", he added.
"The verdict is an opportunity to see what we need to overcome the past".
