John Edward: Language skills essential for global citizens
Scotland's independent schools have a record of academic excellence, and this continued in 2018 with another set of excellent exam results, only reinforced by individual and collective successes in sports, the arts, music and other community endeavours.
With over 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best level of service to their students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen career, and their position as global citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a customized school curriculum, we see world languages continue to be a popular and desirable subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it goes to his head.
If you talk to him in his own language, it goes to his heart".
It is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely on English alone when building relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From this year's recent test scores, we can see that languages are at the top of the league tables with the highest passing rates in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of scholars who studied foreign languages obtained an A above.
The data, collected from SCIS' 74 member schools, showed that 72 percent of students received an A+ in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those studying German, 69 percent of those studying French, and 63 percent of those studying Spanish also received an A.
It shows that independent schools in Scotland are supporting foreign languages as essential skills that children and young adults will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now, as a subject, equally prominent as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering, and mathematics) in independent school curricula and elsewhere.
A survey by the UK Commission for Occupations and Skills in 2014 found that of the reasons workers give for why they struggle to fill jobs, 17 percent are attributed to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly important in preparing young people for their future careers.
With more likely jobs requiring languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career one chooses, learning a second language will be a real asset in the future with such a lifelong skill.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically put a multilingual person above the competition.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of over 4,000 adults in the UK, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage, 15 percent.
That is why it is so important now to invest in language education for today's children.
Knowing several languages, especially those of developing economies, will equip children with a better chance of finding meaningful employment.
In Scotland, each school will differ in the languages it teaches.
A number of schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages considered essential for the UK looking ahead to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be a number of languages to choose from in independent schools, with teaching staff who are specialists in this field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare and equip children with the skills needed to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
It cannot be denied at this stage, in a global business environment, that languages are still hugely important for the future of the country, and therefore this must be reflected in education.
Truly, modern languages should be viewed as "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to Scotland's young people.
It is necessary to do well.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
