North Korea says it 'definitely will not' unilaterally disarm without confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions exacerbate their distrust of the United States and that the country would certainly not unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons without such qualities.
Ri Yong Ho told the world body's annual General Assembly that North Korea has taken "significant goodwill measures" in the past year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, demolishing the nuclear test site, and promising not to proliferate nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"We are not seeing a corresponding response from the US, however", he said.
"Without any confidence in the U.S., there will be no confidence in our national security, and under such circumstances we will certainly not unilaterally disarm first".
While Ri repeated well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phased" approach to denuclearization that would reward North Korea for taking gradual steps, his words seemed significant in that it did not unconditionally reject unilateral denuclearization as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri was referring to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the very first summit between a US president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore when Kim pledged to work for the "destruction of nuclear weapons on the Korean peninsula" while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea wants a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to relax tough international sanctions against North Korea.
"The US is insisting on the 'destruction of nuclear weapons first' and exerting more pressure by tightening the level of sanctions to achieve its goal in a forceful way, and even objecting to the 'declaration of the end of the war,'" Ri said.
"The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a dream of those who are ignorant of us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions are exacerbating our mistrust".
Ri did not say anything about plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump that the US leader drew attention to at the United Nations earlier in the week.
Instead, the minister drew attention to three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in during the past five months, adding: "If the party in this issue of destruction of nuclear weapons had been South Korea and not the US, the destruction of nuclear weapons in the Korean peninsula would not have reached such a dead end".
The tone of Ri's speech was dramatically different from last year, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable that North Korea's missiles would be directed at the US landmass after "Mr. Evil President" Trump called Kim a "fire-man" on a suicide mission.
At the United Nations this year, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, lavishly praised Kim for his courage in taking steps to disarm, but said that much work remains to be done and that sanctions must remain in place until North Korea eliminates nuclear weapons.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no time frame for this, saying "It doesn't matter if it takes two years, three years or five months".
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps it has taken.
However, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday that "the Security Council's enforcement of sanctions must continue vigorously and without pause until we realize the full, final, verified destruction of nuclear weapons".
The Security Council has unanimously tightened sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in an attempt to dry up funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and subsequently said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip there did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying that progress had been made, but North Korea accused him of making "disrespectful demands" just hours later.
North Korea pledged in a meeting with Moon to dismantle a missile site and also a nuclear complex if the United States takes "conforming measures".
He said Kim told him that the "matching measures" he wants to see are security guarantees Trump promised in Singapore as well as steps toward normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on getting enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year is allowing all undergraduates to get more sleep in an attempt to counter the growing macho culture of studying by caffeine-driven "night sessions".
An academic found that students at the world's top university are often uninformed when it comes to the basic principles of how to care for themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a talk on the effect of sleep deprivation on learning.
'At the end of it, a girl approached me and said, 'Why are they telling me this now, in my senior year?'
She said that no one had ever told her how important sleep is - which surprised me,' he told The Telegraph.
The course, offered for the first time this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, as well as improve their general well- being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said that the university decided to introduce the course after finding that students were severely sleep deprived during the week.
The hour-long course includes some interactive tasks.
In one section, there is a picture of a dormitory, where students have to click on coffee cups, curtains, training shoes and books to be told about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by sleep deprivation and the importance of a sleep routine.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase risks of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
A map of the campus, with interactive icons, then encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know it won't change student behavior immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know - just as you have a right to know the health effects of choosing to smoke cigarettes,' added Prof. Czeisler.
The culture of pride in 'studying all night' still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressures on students have meant that sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
Ensuring adequate and quality sleep should be a student's "secret weapon" in avoiding stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, he said - even avoiding them to gain weight, since sleep deprivation puts the brain in starvation mode, leaving you hungry all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after walking one of his classes last year, during his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course opened his eyes and inspired him to pursue a campus-wide course.
The next step, he hopes, is to require all graduate students to complete a similar program of study before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider setting an alarm for when they go to sleep, as well as when to wake up, and to be aware of the harmful effect of 'blue light' emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can disrupt your circadian rhythm and cause you to struggle to touch the sheep.
