The Almanac: The Inventor of the Geiger counter
And now a page from our "Sunday Morning" almanac: September 30, 1882, 136 years ago today, and TODAY . . . the day on which the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method of detecting and measuring radioactivity, an invention that eventually led to the device called the Geiger counter.
Since then, the Geiger counter has been a mainstay of science, and it has also become a mainstay of pop culture, as in the 1950 movie "Bells of Coronado", which starred those two unlikely cowboy scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans:
Man: "What on earth is that?"
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter used to detect radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
When you put these headphones on, you can even hear the effect of the atoms emitted by the radioactivity in the minerals.
Evans: "Gee, it's about to crack!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, just a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name lives on.
New cancer drug can teach the immune system to 'see' predatory cells
A new cancer vaccine can teach the immune system to 'see' and kill predatory cells
As part of treatment, vaccine teaches immune system to identify rogue cells
Method involves extracting immune cells from a patient, changing them in a laboratory
They can then 'see' a protein that is common to many cancers and then inject it back
An experimental vaccine shows promising results in patients with a variety of cancers.
One woman treated with the vaccine, which teaches the immune system to identify predatory cells, saw her ovarian cancer disappear for more than 18 months.
The method involves extracting immune cells from a patient, modifying them in the laboratory so that they can "see" a protein found in many cancers called HER2, and then injecting the cells again.
Professor Jay Berzofsky, of the U.S. National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: "Our results indicate that we have a very promising vaccine".
HER2 "drives the growth of several types of cancers", including breast, ovarian, lung, and colorectal cancers, explained Prof. Berzofsky.
A similar approach to removing immune cells from patients and "teaching" them how to attack cancer cells has worked to beat a type of leukemia.
