National Trust is listening to the secret life of bats
New research is being carried out on a Scottish Highland estate that aims to reveal how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
It is hoped that the findings will shed new light on the behavior of the unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
The study by scientists at the National Trust for Scotland will follow the common and superior damselfly as well as the brown langour and Daubenton bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at key locations on the property to track bat activities throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also carry out mobile surveys using hand-held indicators.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will check the frequency of the bat flocks and determine which species do what.
A habitat map and report will then be compiled to create a detailed landscape-scale picture of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, a conservation consultant for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important to the bats and how they are used by each of the species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management such as grassland creation and how best to manage forest lands for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and throughout the UK have declined significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects sleeping and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lightning can also pose a risk, as can flypaper and some chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are not really blind.
However, their nocturnal hunting activities make their ears more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echo - orientation technique to identify bugs and obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens, and 76,000 acres [16 km 2] of land throughout the country, is very serious about bats.
It has ten trained experts who regularly conduct surveys and sleep inspections and occasionally perform rescues.
The organization even established Scotland's first and only dedicated bat reserve at Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
Estate manager David Thompson says that the estate is the ideal site for them.
"Here in Threave we have a wonderful area for bats", he said.
"We have the old buildings, lots of veteran trees and all the good habitat.
But there is so much about bats that is still unknown, so the work we do here and on other properties helps us better understand what they need to thrive".
He stresses the need to search for bats before doing maintenance in properties because it is possible that the unintentional destruction of a single nest may mean the death of up to 400 females and young and may wipe out an entire local population.
Bats are protected, and it is illegal to kill, disturb, or interdict them or destroy their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish officer of the Bat Conservation Trust, urged the public to jump in to help.
She said: "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of our species we don't know how their populations are doing.
