Fishing and farming are the mainstays of the economy of Central Sulawesi province, especially the coastal area of Donggala.
Nickel mining is also important in the province, but is mostly concentrated in Morowali, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
Palu and Donggala have been hit by tsunamis several times during the past 100 years, according to Indonesia's Disaster Mitigation Agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed over 200 people and destroyed hundreds of houses in Donggala.
A tsunami also hit western Donggala in 1996, killing nine people.
Indonesia sits on the seismic Pacific Ring of Fire and is regularly struck by earthquakes.
Here are some of the major earthquakes and tsunamis of recent years:
2004: A major earthquake along the western coast of Indonesian Aceh province in northern Sumatra on 26 December resulted in a tsunami that struck 14 countries, resulting in 226,000 deaths along the Indian Ocean coast, with more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: A series of strong quakes struck the western coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Hundreds died on Nias Island, off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A magnitude 6.8 earthquake struck south of Java, Indonesia's most populous island, resulting in a tsunami that hit the southern coast and caused nearly 700 deaths.
2009: A 7.6-magnitude earthquake struck near the city of Padang, capital of West Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people died.
2010: A 7.5 magnitude quake struck one of the Mentawai Islands, near Sumatra, leading to a tsunami of up to 10 metres (33 ft) that destroyed dozens of villages and led to about 300 deaths.
2016: A flat earthquake struck the Pidie Jaya Regency in Aceh, leading to destruction and panic as people were reminded of the destruction of the deadly 2004 earthquake and tsunami.
